In conclusion, the literature consistently demonstrates that feature-level multimodal fusion represents a sophisticated evolution from simple data concatenation. Whether through statistical variable selection, classical machine learning on concatenated features, or advanced deep learning architectures employing complex attention and cross-attention mechanisms, the core principle remains the same: the intelligent extraction and combination of the most salient, complementary information from heterogeneous sources creates a joint representation that is greater than the sum of its parts. The shift from CNNs to Vision Transformers, and now to Mamba-based state space models, reflects a continuous effort to capture more nuanced, long-range, and contextual inter-modal relationships while managing computational cost. This paradigm is robustly validated across an extraordinarily diverse spectrum of applications, from mineral analysis and remote sensing to food safety and agricultural management, solidifying feature-level fusion as a critical tool for the future of analytical and classification sciences.

