Feature-Level Multimodal Data Fusion: A Methodological Taxonomy and Review
Feature-level fusion, or mid-level fusion, constitutes a computational approach that merges multiple feature vectors from dissimilar origins or distinct neural network stages into a harmonized representation. This strategy has proven remarkably versatile across disciplines, consistently outperforming single-sensor analyses by capturing complementary physicochemical information. Rather than organizing these works by application domain, we structure this review according to the methodological resemblance of their fusion architectures, progressing from classical feature concatenation to increasingly sophisticated deep learning mechanisms. This taxonomy reveals an evolutionary trajectory in the field, where each successive approach addresses the limitations of its predecessors while building upon their foundational insights.

I. Classical Feature Extraction and Concatenation Approaches
The most foundational implementation of feature-level fusion involves the independent extraction of discriminative features from each modality, followed by their direct concatenation into a unified vector for subsequent modeling. This family of approaches shares a common philosophy: that intelligent pre-fusion dimensionality reduction and feature selection can eliminate noise and redundancy while preserving complementary information, thereby creating a more effective input than raw spectral concatenation.

Fuentes et al. (2022), in their work "Laser-Induced Breakdown Spectroscopy and Hyperspectral Imaging Data Fusion for improved Mineralogical Analysis of Copper Concentrates," provide a paradigmatic example of this philosophy applied to mineral quantification. Their mid-level data fusion strategy employed the competitive adaptive reweighted sampling (CARS) algorithm to select only 25 key wavelengths from LIBS spectra and 25 from HSI spectra, creating a compact 50-variable input for an artificial neural network. This deliberate reduction of the feature space—from over 300 raw wavelengths to just 50—proved decisively superior to low-level fusion of full spectra, as it eliminated noise-dominated variables while retaining the elemental and molecular information most relevant to predicting mineral species concentrations. The approach embodies the core rationale for feature-level over low-level fusion: computational efficiency and model generalizability are enhanced by stripping away non-informative variance before the integration step.

Building upon this same principle of selective feature concatenation but extending it to a three-technique system, Feng et al. (2020), in "Investigation on Data Fusion of Multisource Spectral Data for Rice Leaf Diseases Identification Using Machine Learning Methods," systematically explored the fusion of PCA-derived and autoencoder-derived features from hyperspectral imaging, mid-infrared spectroscopy, and laser-induced breakdown spectroscopy for rice disease classification. Their comprehensive experimental design revealed a crucial nuance: the concatenation of PCA features from HSI and MIR produced optimal results, whereas adding LIBS features sometimes degraded performance, suggesting that the marginal benefit of an additional modality depends on whether it introduces complementary or redundant information. This work established that successful feature concatenation requires not merely the accumulation of data sources but a judicious evaluation of their information complementarity—a finding that resonates throughout the subsequent literature.

A related concatenation strategy, but one that introduces the concept of learnable fusion weights, is presented by Zhang et al. (2022) in "End-to-End Fusion of Hyperspectral and Chlorophyll Fluorescence Imaging to Identify Rice Stresses." Their mid-level fusion architecture employed four parallel CNN sub-models to extract 128-dimensional deep features from leaf and stem spectra of both hyperspectral and chlorophyll fluorescence imaging. These four feature vectors are then multiplied by learnable weights (W₁ through W₄) before concatenation into a single fused representation. The learnable weighting mechanism represents a conceptual bridge between static concatenation and the dynamic attention-based approaches that would follow; it allows the model to adaptively emphasize more informative modalities while suppressing less reliable ones, all within an end-to-end trainable framework that eliminates the manual feature engineering required by classical approaches.

Liu et al. (2022) further validate the efficacy of classical concatenation for provenance determination in their article "Combined laser-induced breakdown spectroscopy and hyperspectral imaging with machine learning for the classification and identification of rice geographical origin." By concatenating 25 elemental emission line intensities from LIBS with 378 reflectance wavelengths from HSI, they created a fused feature matrix that captured both the atomic composition and molecular structure of rice samples. The resulting 99.85% classification accuracy across six geographical origins—a substantial improvement over LIBS (93.06%) and HSI (88.07%) alone—demonstrates that even straightforward feature concatenation can be remarkably effective when the selected features represent genuinely orthogonal and complementary aspects of sample chemistry.

Li et al. (2022), in "Combining Vis-NIR and NIR hyperspectral imaging techniques with a data fusion strategy for the rapid qualitative evaluation of multiple qualities in chicken," offer a systematic comparison that reinforces the conditional superiority of intermediate-level fusion. After applying various feature wavelength selection algorithms to Vis-NIR and NIR hyperspectral data, they concatenated the selected variables for PLSR modeling. Their results revealed that the optimal fusion level is analyte-dependent: while low-level fusion performed best for predicting total viable count, intermediate-level fusion was unequivocally superior for predicting total volatile basic nitrogen. This finding underscores that feature-level fusion is particularly advantageous when the chemical basis of a quality parameter is distributed across distinct spectral regions, such that the concatenation of specific, informative wavelengths provides a more parsimonious and predictive model than full-spectrum fusion.

II. Cross-Modal Attention and Transformer-Based Fusion Architectures
While concatenation-based approaches treat the fused features as independent contributors to a joint representation, a more recent paradigm shift has emerged around attention mechanisms that explicitly model the relationships between modalities during the fusion process. These architectures recognize that the complementarity between, for example, HSI and LiDAR data stems not only from the coexistence of spectral and elevation information but from their spatial correspondence: the reflectance spectrum at a given pixel is inherently linked to the height of the structure at that location. By learning attention scores that govern how features from one modality inform the representation of another, these methods achieve a deeper, more context-aware fusion.

Mohla et al. (2020) pioneered this direction in "FusAtNet: Dual Attention based SpectroSpatial Multimodal Fusion Network for Hyperspectral and LiDAR Classification." Their architecture operates in two sequential attention stages at the feature level. First, a self-attention module processes HSI data to generate a spectral attention mask that highlights its own informative spectral features. Simultaneously, a cross-attention module processes LiDAR data to produce a spatial attention mask that accentuates the HSI's spatial characteristics. These attentive feature maps are then concatenated with the original data before being passed to a second-stage modality attention module. The key innovation lies in the bidirectional nature of the fusion: HSI features are refined not only by their own spectral saliency but also by the spatial structure derived from LiDAR, creating a fused representation where each modality's strengths compensate for the other's limitations.

Yang et al. (2024) extend this cross-attention paradigm to the transformer domain in their "Modality Fusion Vision Transformer for Hyperspectral and LiDAR Data Collaborative Classification" (MFViT). Their stackable Modality Fusion Block introduces a critical refinement to conventional cross-attention. Recognizing that mapping heterogeneous HSI and LiDAR features into a shared subspace is inherently challenging—especially with limited training data—they design an asymmetric cross-attention mechanism where LiDAR features serve as both query and key to generate an attention map, while HSI features act as the value. This design exploits the spatial alignment between the modalities without requiring them to be expressed in a common feature space. The LiDAR-derived attention map, which captures structure and elevation, is used to reweight the HSI features, effectively injecting 3D spatial context into the spectral representation. This approach achieves state-of-the-art classification accuracies of 99.91% on the Trento dataset, demonstrating that feature-level fusion can be most effective when it respects the inherent asymmetry and complementarity of the modalities rather than forcing them into a homogeneous representation.

Huo et al. (2023) push the concept of cross-modal attention to its logical extreme in "Multimodal Hyperspectral Image Classification via Interconnected Fusion." Their Interconnected Fusion (IF) framework generates not a single attention map but an entire 3×3 fusion matrix of nine interconnected feature representations. By computing self-attention (intra-modality) and cross-attention (inter-modality) among three inputs—the HSI patch, its center patch, and the corresponding LiDAR patch—they create a comprehensive feature map that captures both intra-modal self-similarity and inter-modal cross-correlations at multiple spatial scales. These nine interrelated feature perspectives are then compressed through a feature fusion layer into a single integrated representation. The genius of this approach is that the nine elements in the fusion matrix can complement each other and collectively eliminate biases that any single perspective might introduce. For example, an HSI-LiDAR cross-attention element might incorrectly emphasize a shadow region, but this bias is counterbalanced by the center-patch-to-LiDAR cross-attention that captures broader contextual information. This framework achieves remarkable performance, with overall accuracies of 97.50% on the Houston dataset, illustrating the power of exhaustively modeling all possible inter-modal relationships.

Roy et al. (2024) introduce a conceptually distinct but equally innovative paradigm in "Multimodal Fusion Transformer for Remote Sensing Image Classification" (MFT). Instead of performing cross-attention between modality-specific feature maps, they use the LiDAR data to directly generate the external classification (CLS) token that is prepended to the HSI patch tokens in the transformer encoder. The CLS token, which traditionally aggregates global image information for classification, is thus initialized with elevation-derived features rather than random values. During the multi-head self-attention process, this LiDAR-informed CLS token queries the HSI patch tokens, creating a fusion mechanism where the elevation context actively guides the extraction and weighting of spectral-spatial features. This approach elegantly circumvents the need for separate fusion modules by embedding the fusion process directly into the transformer's core attention mechanism, achieving superior generalization across diverse datasets including Houston, Trento, MUUFL, and Augsburg.

Liu et al. (2025), in "Multimodal Prompt Tuning for Hyperspectral and LiDAR Classification," advance a two-stage strategy that separates representation learning from modality adaptation. In the first stage, a spatial-spectral transformer is pre-trained on multiple HSI-only datasets to learn transferable features across diverse scenes. In the second stage, LiDAR data is introduced not through concatenation or cross-attention but as a prompt—a compact, lightweight signal that modulates the pre-trained HSI representations. A small CNN extracts a feature vector from the LiDAR patch, which then serves as the key and value in a cross-attention operation at every transformer layer, dynamically tuning the HSI features to incorporate elevation context. This prompt-based fusion represents a significant advance in parameter efficiency: only the LiDAR feature extractor and cross-attention layers are trained in the second stage, while the bulk of the network remains frozen. The resulting model achieves state-of-the-art performance (92.21% OA on Houston) while requiring far fewer trainable parameters than fully fine-tuned alternatives, making it particularly attractive for scenarios with limited co-registered HSI-LiDAR data.

Wang et al. (2023) hybridize CNN and transformer architectures in their "Multi-modal transformer cascaded fusion net (MMTCFN) for fusion and classification of multi-modal remote sensing data." Their two-stage design first uses a three-branch cascaded CNN to extract shallow modality-specific features—spectral from HSI, spatial from HSI, and elevation from LiDAR. These features are then concatenated and passed to a Vectorized Pixel Group Transformer (VPGT) for deep feature-level fusion. The VPGT introduces a vectorized pixel group embedding that preserves spatial detail by treating each pixel as an independent token rather than partitioning the feature map into coarse patches, enabling finer-grained cross-modal interaction. By combining CNN-based local feature extraction with transformer-based global feature fusion, this architecture captures both fine spatial-spectral details and long-range cross-modal dependencies. The incorporation of the DropKey mechanism into the multi-head self-attention further alleviates overfitting, yielding strong performance even with imbalanced training samples.

III. Efficient and State-Space Fusion Architectures
While transformer-based fusion methods achieve remarkable accuracy, their quadratic computational complexity with respect to sequence length poses challenges for practical deployment, especially with high-resolution data. A nascent but rapidly growing body of work addresses this limitation by developing fusion mechanisms that maintain the modeling power of attention-based methods while drastically reducing computational cost.

Wang et al. (2025) lead this direction in "CSFMAMBA: CROSS STATE FUSION MAMBA OPERATOR FOR MULTIMODAL REMOTE SENSING IMAGE CLASSIFICATION." Their Cross State Fusion Mamba (CSFMamba) network leverages the Mamba state space model, which achieves linear computational complexity by introducing a hidden state space that processes sequences without computing pairwise attention scores. The key innovation is a cross-state module where the CLS token from one modality is spliced into the token set of the other modality, and the state transition parameters (B, C, Δ) of the receiving modality are computed from this cross-modal token set. This allows the state space of one modality to be directly informed by the features of another without the O(N²) cost of cross-attention. The result is a fusion mechanism that achieves 93.38% OA on the Houston2018 dataset with only 0.219M parameters and 12.29M FLOPs—orders of magnitude less than comparable transformer models—demonstrating that efficient fusion architectures can achieve competitive performance with dramatically reduced computational burden.

Yin et al. (2025) address a different dimension of efficiency in "A lightweight hyperspectral image multi-layer feature fusion classification method based on spatial and channel reconstruction." Although their SCNet operates on single-modality HSI data, their Multi-Layer Feature Fusion (MLFF) unit embodies principles directly applicable to multimodal fusion. The MLFF concatenates feature maps from multiple SCConv modules at different network depths, aggregating hierarchical information from shallow spatial details to deep semantic abstractions. This internal feature-level fusion is performed with spatial and channel reconstruction convolutions that systematically reduce redundancy in both dimensions, achieving classification accuracies exceeding 98% on the Pavia University dataset with only 43,425 parameters. The methodological insight is that effective fusion requires not just combining features but actively pruning redundant information—a principle that extends naturally to multimodal settings where inter-modal redundancy is pervasive.

IV. Beyond Classification: Knowledge Distillation and Cross-Modal Generation
The most transformative approaches to feature-level fusion are those that transcend the need for multi-sensor deployment altogether, using one modality to enhance another in ways that persist even when the enhancing modality is no longer available.

Lopes et al. (2024), in "From sensor fusion to knowledge distillation in collaborative LIBS and hyperspectral imaging for mineral identification," present a multimodal spectral knowledge distillation pipeline that serves as a capstone to the methodological evolution described above. They first use LIBS—the more interpretable and accurate technique—to perform unsupervised K-means clustering and generate high-quality mineral labels. These labels then serve as training targets for a supervised PLS-DA model that takes only HSI data as input. The result is an HSI-based classifier that achieves performance comparable to LIBS while operating at the throughput and acquisition speed of HSI. This approach inverts the traditional fusion paradigm: instead of permanently coupling modalities at inference time, it uses the superior modality as a transient supervisor to enhance the inferior one, after which the superior modality can be removed. The practical implication is profound—it enables the deployment of high-performance, single-sensor systems that have indirectly benefited from multimodal information, dramatically reducing hardware costs while maintaining analytical quality.

Neo et al. (2023) extend this concept to synthetic data generation in "Cross-modal generative models for multi-modal plastic sorting." Their Spectral Conversion Autoencoder (SCAE) learns to translate between spectral modalities—for example, generating synthetic Raman and LIBS spectra from FTIR input. These generated spectra, when fused with the original FTIR data in a decision-level multimodal classification framework, improved accuracy from 0.933 to 0.963. The SCAE approach shares with Lopes et al. (2024) the fundamental insight that multimodality need not imply multi-sensor deployment; generative models can simulate the complementary information that additional sensors would provide, enabling more robust fusion without the associated hardware costs.

Synthesis
The methodological trajectory traced in this review reveals a field evolving from simplicity to sophistication, from concatenation to contextualization, and from multi-sensor dependence to multi-sensor empowerment. Early concatenation approaches established the fundamental principle that combining orthogonal features from different modalities yields superior predictive performance. Attention-based architectures built upon this by recognizing that features should not merely coexist in a joint vector but should actively inform and refine each other through learned cross-modal relationships. Efficient architectures responded to the computational challenges of these powerful but demanding models, developing fusion mechanisms that preserve performance while drastically reducing resource requirements. Finally, knowledge distillation and cross-modal generation have liberated fusion from the requirement of permanent multi-sensor deployment, enabling single-sensor systems to benefit from multimodal knowledge acquired during training.

This evolution reflects a deepening understanding that the power of feature-level fusion resides not in the accumulation of data but in the intelligent orchestration of complementary information—whether that orchestration is achieved through variable selection, attention mechanisms, state-space dynamics, or teacher-student knowledge transfer. As the field advances, the boundary between "multimodal" and "unimodal" systems may increasingly blur, with models trained on heterogeneous sensor suites but deployed on minimal hardware configurations, democratizing access to high-performance analytical capabilities across industrial, agricultural, and scientific domains.




