A parallel narrative of development is vividly illustrated in the domain of food safety, specifically in the evaluation of meat quality. Li et al. (2022), in their work "Combining Vis-NIR and NIR hyperspectral imaging techniques with a data fusion strategy for the rapid qualitative evaluation of multiple qualities in chicken", present a classic case study of comparing fusion levels. Their objective was to predict total volatile basic nitrogen (TVB-N) and total viable count (TVC) in chicken fillets. After preprocessing and feature wavelength selection using algorithms like CARS and Random Frog, they concatenated the selected variables into an intermediate-level fusion dataset for Partial Least Squares Regression (PLSR) modeling. The results delineated a clear hierarchy: while low-level fusion was optimal for predicting TVC, the intermediate-level fusion strategy was unequivocally superior for predicting TVB-N, achieving an Rp² of 0.8652. This outcome affirms that the optimal fusion level can be analyte-dependent, yet feature-level fusion often provides the best balance between reducing irrelevant noisy variables and preserving the critical, synergistic chemical information from different near-infrared spectral regions.

The transition from classical machine learning to advanced deep learning architectures has further refined and expanded the power of feature-level fusion. Zhao et al. (2022), in their "Joint classification of hyperspectral and LiDAR data using a hierarchical CNN and transformer" (HCT), and the foundational work by Mohla et al. (2020) in "FusAtNet: Dual Attention based SpectroSpatial Multimodal Fusion Network for Hyperspectral and LiDAR Classification", pioneered this shift. While FusAtNet explicitly utilizes cross-attention mechanisms to fuse self-attention maps from HSI with LiDAR-derived spatial attention masks at different stages, the underlying principle of extracting and combining modality-specific features is isomorphic to the mid-level pipeline. This concept is implemented in a more structurally explicit manner by Yin et al. (2025) in their lightweight network, "A lightweight hyperspectral image multi-layer feature fusion classification method based on spatial and channel reconstruction". Their SCNet architecture incorporates a multi-layer feature fusion unit that concatenates feature maps generated at different depths of convolutional modules, including spatial and channel reconstruction convolutions. This internal feature fusion strategy within a unimodal HSI classification network mimics the logic of multimodal mid-level fusion, where diverse internal representations (analogous to different modality features) are merged to form a more robust final feature set before the classifier, resulting in high accuracy with remarkably low computational cost.

The zenith of deep learning’s application to this fusion paradigm is the use of Vision Transformers (ViT) to learn and merge global contextual relationships between modality-specific features. Yang et al. (2024) in their "Modality Fusion Vision Transformer for Hyperspectral and LiDAR Data Collaborative Classification" (MFViT) explicitly design a Modality Fusion Block where features from HSI and LiDAR are not simply concatenated, but are fused via a novel cross-attention mechanism. The LiDAR features are used to generate an attention map that refines the HSI’s spatial features at the feature level within the transformer’s sequential flow. This approach is echoed by Huo et al. (2023) in "Multimodal Hyperspectral Image Classification via Interconnected Fusion", whose Interconnected Fusion (IF) framework generates an entire matrix of intra- and inter-modality features through self- and cross-attention. These nine perspectives are then compressed in a feature fusion layer, creating an integrated representation that corrects individual biases. The exceptional performance on the Trento, MUUFL, and Houston datasets confirms that sophisticated feature-level attention-based fusion captures rich, contextual inter-modal relationships that are invisible to simple concatenation.

Addressing the critical barrier of limited co-registered data, which directly hinders the training of robust feature-level fusion models, innovative knowledge-based approaches have been proposed. Lopes et al. (2024), in their study published as "From sensor fusion to knowledge distillation in collaborative LIBS and hyperspectral imaging for mineral identification", present a transformative pipeline called Multimodal Spectral Knowledge Distillation. This method side-steps the need for permanently paired sensor data in the deployment phase. The LIBS modality, acting as a superior "teacher," provides unsupervised labels for training a supervised model on the "student" HSI data. This pipeline effectively transfers the high performance and interpretability of elemental (LIBS) features onto the molecular (HSI) domain, enhancing its classification capacity to a level comparable to LIBS while retaining HSI’s superior throughput. This paradigm, along with the cross-modal generative model proposed by Neo et al. (2023) in "Cross-modal generative models for multi-modal plastic sorting," where a Spectral Conversion Autoencoder (SCAE) generates synthetic features of one modality from another to augment a multi-modal feature-level classifier, points toward a future where feature-level fusion can thrive even with incomplete in-situ data. The synergy created by intelligently mining and fusing heterogeneous features—whether through direct concatenation after variable selection, deep attention-based networks, or knowledge-distilled representations—has unequivocally established feature-level fusion as a cornerstone of modern multimodal spectral analysis, enabling systems that are more accurate, robust, and deployable than ever before.